Signed-off-by: Kostadin Plachkov <k.n.plachkov@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/galenguyer/moby/commits/cd40eb89aea1d5f4fdfe0b0baa5b37ac513f5f75"},{"sha":"0d9b0ed678e2b106e769e974f13aaf100e46351c","author":{"name":"Drew Erny","email":"db55f14336294d3287c922ab67a84bd4af5a0c81@mirantis.com"},"message":"Fix possible overlapping IPs

A node is no longer using its load balancer IP address when it no longer
has tasks that use the network that requires that load balancer. When
this occurs, the swarmkit manager will free that IP in IPAM, and may
reaassign it.

When a task shuts down cleanly, it attempts removal of the networks it
uses, and if it is the last task using those networks, this removal
succeeds, and the load balancer IP is freed.

However, this behavior is absent if the container fails. Removal of the
networks is never attempted.

To address this issue, I amend the executor. Whenever a node load
balancer IP is removed or changed, that information is passedd to the
executor by way of the Configure method. By keeping track of the set of
node NetworkAttachments from the previous call to Configure, we can
determine which, if any, have been removed or changed.

At first, this seems to create a race, by which a task can be attempting
to start and the network is removed right out from under it. However,
this is already addressed in the controller. The controller will attempt
to recreate missing networks before starting a task.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/galenguyer/moby/commits/09191c093645f308e5fbce4275b5cdfefb048a67"},{"sha":"7b071e055716028dc8f45842105cd6ce0ff7db1e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/archive: RebaseArchiveEntries(): ignore G110

    pkg/archive/copy.go:357:16: G110: Potential DoS vulnerability via decompression bomb (gosec)
                if _, err = io.Copy(rebasedTar, srcTar); err != nil {
                            ^

Ignoring GoSec G110. See https://github.com/securego/gosec/pull/433
and https://cure53.de/pentest-report_opa.pdf, which recommends to
replace io.Copy with io.CopyN7. The latter allows to specify the
maximum number of bytes that should be read. By properly defining
the limit, it can be assured that a GZip compression bomb cannot
easily cause a Denial-of-Service.
After reviewing, this should not affect us, because here we do not
read into memory.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 387732203
Change-Id: I263a643988e87124e93a2c8aa7124f943691ead1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/humblefool1998/tensorflow/commits/a86d3765b67b3977ad5afd3ede5561b18b25108e"},{"sha":"76d68c3f2ce78168ffb59f43c39e1ee718c24be1","author":{"name":"Skye Wanderman-Milne","email":"4c878c1ae364587078acae22009e8542fed717b6@google.com"},"message":"[libtpu][PJRT] Use HLO module from serialized executable.

Prior to this change, the caller was responsible for supplying an HLO
module when deserializing a serialized TPU executable, which would be
associated with the resulting executable. This was causing problems
with JAX's new persistent compilation cache, because deserialized
executables would end up with the unoptimized HLO module, instead of
the optimized HLO. This could cause crashes, e.g. when using pjit,
because the optimized module specifies the sharded input/output shapes
but the unoptimized uses the unsharded shapes.

It turns out the optimized module was already included in the
serialized executable (thanks to Qiao for figuring this out). This
change makes the deserialization method use the serialized HLO module
instead of requiring it from the caller.

[{"sha":"2663a12eb3d47d172eb7b3f5137dfc39babed199","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Tweak wording","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tgroshon/react/commits/2663a12eb3d47d172eb7b3f5137dfc39babed199"},{"sha":"970fa122d8188bafa600e9b5214833487fbf1092","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use lanes to check if a render is a Suspense retry (#19307)

Now that Suspense retries have their own dedicated set of lanes
(#19287), we can determine if a render includes only retries by checking
if its lanes are a subset of the retry lanes.

Previously we inferred this by checking
`workInProgressRootLatestProcessedEventTime`. If it's not set, that
implies that no updates were processed in the current render, which
implies it must be a Suspense retry. The eventual plan is to get rid of
`workInProgressRootLatestProcessedEventTime` and instead track event
times on the root; this change is one the steps toward that goal.

The relevant tests were originally added in #15769.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tgroshon/react/commits/970fa122d8188bafa600e9b5214833487fbf1092"},{"sha":"17efbf7d63f3e4abb75b65b9baecdfe1b84fb4d5","author":{"name":"Nick Reiley","email":"b7d4ab92b0d5816b7cc249a203bd96c1bde469c6@gmail.com"},"message":"[DevTools] Show HOC names in profiler (#19283)

As TFLite team delivered the Signature concept recently
(https://www.tensorflow.org/lite/guide/signatures), it is a good time to rethink
about the representative_dataset method behavior.

As per the TensorFlow product design and TensorFlow MLIR behaviors, it is
really impossible to keep the input ordering same as before.

Instead of depending on the tensor indices, it would be better to depend on the
input names, specified in the signature table.

For example,

def representative_dataset():
    for _ in range(100):
      image = np.random.rand(1, 244, 244, 3).astype(np.float32)
      bias = np.random.rand(1, 10).astype(np.float32)
      yield {"image": image, "bias": bias}

Change-Id: I263a643988e87124e93a2c8aa7124f943691ead1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hari0920/tensorflow/commits/a86d3765b67b3977ad5afd3ede5561b18b25108e"},{"sha":"76d68c3f2ce78168ffb59f43c39e1ee718c24be1","author":{"name":"Skye Wanderman-Milne","email":"4c878c1ae364587078acae22009e8542fed717b6@google.com"},"message":"[libtpu][PJRT] Use HLO module from serialized executable.

Prior to this change, the caller was responsible for supplying an HLO
module when deserializing a serialized TPU executable, which would be
associated with the resulting executable. This was causing problems
with JAX's new persistent compilation cache, because deserialized
executables would end up with the unoptimized HLO module, instead of
the optimized HLO. This could cause crashes, e.g. when using pjit,
because the optimized module specifies the sharded input/output shapes
but the unoptimized uses the unsharded shapes.

It turns out the optimized module was already included in the
serialized executable (thanks to Qiao for figuring this out). This
change makes the deserialization method use the serialized HLO module
instead of requiring it from the caller.
